</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE006639%2F1"><gtr:id>9C85EEE9-4264-441A-BB67-B652D3D24F90</gtr:id><gtr:title>Civil Society in Islamic Context</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E006639/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The main problem of the research can be stated as follows: 'how can we utilise the theoretical resources from Development Studies, Social Policy, International Politics, Cultural and Islamic Studies to understand more effectively indigenous forms of associational life based on more religious values, norms and identity?'&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Overall, the research:&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>pursues a debate about ideas surrounding the concept of civil society in poverty alleviation and welfare strategy terms from within a global perspective whilst complementing the discussion by looking more closely at specific local manifestations of that debate in the context of Bangladesh; &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>challenges the development arena and its current measures for the promotion of civil society within a development policy network where multiple international and local actors take part; &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>analyses the ?crowding out? effects of a predominantly secular development framework and practice on indigenous forms of associational life; and finally, &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>explores possibilities of Islamic forms of civil societies. This provides a rich analysis on the ?quality of governance aid being provided in non-western context? based on methodologically innovative, theoretically well-informed, historically aware, pragmatic and critical research.&lt;/li>
